The paper discusses the potential of the cybernetic method of inquiry for natural resource governance, which involves systems thinking and modeling. This suggests that the paper may fall under the category of systems and control (cs.SY) or cybernetics (cs.CY). The paper also mentions the use of game theory and learning in games, which could place it under the categories of game theory (cs.GT) or social and information networks (cs.SI). Finally, the paper discusses policy guidelines for avoiding Tragedy of the Commons scenarios, which suggests a focus on social and economic systems and could place it under the category of social computing (cs.SOC).
